  "prompt": "What evidence can be provided by India to prove the claimed surgical strikes in PoK?",
  "response": "The Indian government has provided several pieces of evidence to support its claim of conducting surgical strikes in Pakistan-occupied Kashmir (PoK) in September 2016. These include:\n\n1. **Official Statements**: The Indian government, through the Director General of Military Operations (DGMO), officially announced the surgical strikes on September 29, 2016. The statement detailed the operation's objectives and outcomes.\n\n2. **Video Footage**: In 2018, the Indian government released a video showing Indian Special Forces crossing the Line of Control (LoC) and targeting terrorist launch pads. The footage was intended to provide visual proof of the operation's success.\n\n3. **Eyewitness Accounts**: Indian soldiers who participated in the operation provided testimonies and descriptions of the mission, further corroborating the government's claims.\n\n4. **Intelligence Reports**: India cited intelligence reports indicating a significant reduction in terrorist activities in the region following the strikes, suggesting the operation disrupted militant infrastructure.\n\n5. **International Reactions**: While Pakistan denied the surgical strikes, several international observers and analysts acknowledged the operation based on circumstantial evidence and India's consistent stance.\n\n6. **Operational Logs and Documentation**: Details of the planning, execution, and aftermath of the strikes were reportedly documented by the Indian military, though these remain classified for security reasons.\n\nIndia's evidence primarily relies on official statements, released footage, and strategic outcomes, though some sources remain classified to protect military operations and personnel.",
